# Feature Scope: Agentic Code Review Assistant

## Core Features (MVP — building now)

Priority levels: **P0** = must-have for the pipeline to function · **P1** = needed for
production quality · **P2** = important but can ship without

### F-01 · GitHub App Webhook Integration `P0`

**Acceptance criteria:** A PR opened/updated on any installed repo triggers a job within
5s; webhook always returns HTTP 202 in under 1s regardless of pipeline duration.
A closed/merged PR triggers embedding cleanup within 30s.

- Handle PR events: `opened`, `synchronize`, `reopened` → enqueue review job
- Handle PR event: `closed` (merged or closed) → enqueue embedding cleanup job
- Each `synchronize` review covers the **full base→head diff**, not just the incremental push
- Immediately return HTTP 202; enqueue async review job to Upstash Redis
- GitHub App JWT authentication + per-installation access tokens
- Fetch PR diff (unified format), changed file list, and base-branch file tree from GitHub REST API
- Post line-level review comments and a summary PR review via GitHub Review API

### F-02 · Multi-Agent Review Pipeline (LangGraph OSS) `P0`

**Acceptance criteria:** A real PR diff produces structured findings from at least one
specialist agent; SynthesisAgent output posts to GitHub without contradiction errors.

- **SupervisorAgent**: reads diff metadata (file types, change volume, modified paths) and decides which specialist agents to invoke; avoids running all agents on every PR
- **SecurityAgent**: OWASP Top 10 violations, hardcoded secrets/credentials, injection flaws (SQL/command/path), insecure deserialization, use of vulnerable patterns
- **PerfAgent**: N+1 query patterns, algorithmic complexity regressions, blocking I/O in async contexts, inefficient data structures, unnecessary re-renders (React)
- **ArchAgent**: layer violations (e.g. DB calls in route handlers), tight coupling, circular dependencies, separation of concerns, naming and module boundary conventions
- **TestAgent**: missing tests for changed public functions, missing edge cases, poor/missing assertions, test-to-code ratio regression
- **SynthesisAgent**: deduplicates findings across agents, assigns final severity (Critical / High / Medium / Low / Info), formats structured review with fix suggestions, resolves agent contradictions

### F-03 · Code Context & RAG `P1`

**Acceptance criteria:** SecurityAgent retrieves auth-related context files not in the
diff; embedding lookup latency < 500ms per agent query; embeddings are deleted within
30s of PR close.

- tree-sitter AST parsing for **Python** and **JavaScript/TypeScript** — chunk at function/class boundaries, not character count
- Each agent receives a structured Review Package: PR metadata + changed context units (full old+new function bodies from tree-sitter) + agent-specific RAG context (top-5 related chunks)
- Embed changed files + 1-hop import graph into pgvector (Neon Postgres), keyed by commit SHA
- Per-agent RAG retrieval: each agent queries only relevant context (SecurityAgent → auth/crypto patterns; PerfAgent → DB/loop patterns; ArchAgent → imports/class hierarchy)
- Hybrid diff handling: full package for PRs ≤50 files; batch per 10 files for larger PRs
- **Embedding cleanup**: on `pull_request.closed`, delete all `code_embeddings` rows for `(repository_id, head_sha)`; weekly background job clears rows older than 30 days

### F-04 · Structured Review Output `P0`

**Acceptance criteria:** Every finding posted to GitHub has severity, category, file path,
line range, description, and fix suggestion; re-reviewing the same commit SHA is a no-op.

- Every finding includes: `severity`, `category` (security/perf/arch/test), `file`, `line_range`, `description`, `fix_suggestion`, `agent_source`
- Line-level GitHub comments on specific diff lines where applicable
- Single summarizing PR review body posted as a GitHub review (COMMENT status)
- Idempotent per commit SHA: skip re-review unless forced

### F-05 · Async Worker System `P0`

**Acceptance criteria:** A job enqueued to Redis is picked up by the worker within 10s;
failed jobs retry up to 3 times with backoff; job state is always queryable from the DB.

- Webhook handler enqueues job; Upstash Redis as queue
- Worker process consumes queue, runs LangGraph pipeline, updates job status
- Job states: `pending → running → completed | failed`
- Retry with exponential backoff on transient failures (max 3 attempts)
- Job status and results persisted in PostgreSQL

### F-06 · Web Dashboard (React + Vite + TypeScript) `P1`

**Acceptance criteria:** A logged-in user can see all reviews for their repos, toggle
agents per repo, and navigate to a review detail page with per-finding breakdown.

- **Auth**: GitHub OAuth via GitHub App — login required to access dashboard
- **Repositories**: list installed repos, enable/disable review per repo
- **Agent config**: toggle which agents run per repo (Security, Perf, Arch, Test)
- **Review history**: paginated list of past reviews per repo (date, PR#, severity summary)
- **Review detail**: full review findings, per-agent breakdown, severity distribution, Langfuse trace link
- **GitHub App install flow**: guided install link for new orgs/repos

### F-07 · Observability & Storage `P0`

**Acceptance criteria:** Every PR review produces a Langfuse trace with per-agent spans
and token counts; all reviews and findings are queryable from the DB indefinitely.

- Langfuse Cloud (free tier) tracing: one trace per PR review, one span per agent node
- Track per-agent token usage and latency
- All reviews persisted in PostgreSQL: full findings JSON, metadata, timestamps

### F-08 · Evaluation System `P2`

**Acceptance criteria:** `make eval` runs against all 20 golden PRs and reports
precision/recall per agent category; false positive rate is tracked per run.

- Synthetic golden set: ~20 hand-crafted known-bad PRs covering each agent's domain
- Langfuse datasets + LLM-as-judge scoring for each review run against golden set
- CLI command `make eval` runs the full eval suite and reports precision/recall per category
- Track false positive rate per agent category over time

